    {
      "start_time": 152.0,
      "end_time": 190.0,
      "transcript": "On the cover of your book, they did something really clever on the Korean version where each letter is made out of one of the six materials that you say make up the modern world. So there's oil, copper, iron, lithium, salt, and sand. But what really surprised me among these six elements was sand. Because you don't think of sand as something that's a valuable material. But once I read your book, I started seeing sand all around us. First of all, Korean economy these days is basically built on semiconductors. and people think about semiconductors as this very important intellectual property but people don't think of the silicon the sand it's actually made out of and if you I mean you've been in uh Seoul so you know that we have very few buildings unlike in the UK that's built out of bricks or stone or or wood most of our buildings are built out of concrete and glass and I didn't think about it but glass is sand and concrete is sand right mostly sand so after reading your book I was driving down Seoul and I was thinking we're living in Dune.",
      "summary": "The host discusses the book cover design featuring the six materials and expresses surprise at the importance of sand, noting its role in semiconductors, glass, and concrete in Seoul."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 190.0,
      "end_time": 228.0,
      "transcript": "Seoul is a sand city. We are basically Freeman. Yeah. Yeah. Is it he who controls the spice? It's the spice as well, isn't? Oh, that's true. In Korea, Spice and Sand. in Korea. It's spicy.",
