    {
      "start_time": 228.0,
      "end_time": 266.0,
      "transcript": "They have to create a type of light that doesn't exist in the atmosphere to beam it, to kind of fry these different transistors onto the chip. But the funny thing was, talking to people who worked in this world of microchips, I would say, where does the silicon in a silicon chip come from? It's a pretty simple question. And most people who work in silicon chips, they didn't really know the answer. They were just like, well, it's probably just sand. But the reality is it's a very particular type of sand. Actually, it's not really sand. It's something called quartzite, big lumps of quartz that come out of the ground. And because of the distance between the people who are kind of making the microchips and the people who are getting the rocks out of the ground, and because there's numerous different companies and processes that it goes through to get there, that's actually a really complex story. But inside each of our pockets, even before you get to that fab, you know, Taiwan or here in Korea, even before you get to that fab, you need to take a lump of rock out of the ground and turn it into a perfect silicon wafer. the silicon wafers you've probably seen you know those round little bits of metal that then eventually become silicon wafers and i've always wondered actually why is it round it's because the process in order to kind of get that rock so basically you take the rock you put take it out of the ground you blast it from a quarry you send it to a kind of refining plant where it gets turned into something called metallurgical silicon that's 99.9 pure that sounds pretty pure it's not pure enough you need to refine it again you turn it into something called polysilicon that's 99.999999 nine i'm losing track of how many nights it's like 10 nines of purity you do something called the chakrowski process which means lifting it up with a seed crystal and turning it turning it turning it all the way and eventually from this molten pool of silicon you get this long kind of like a sausage almost that then you slice up and up and up but that that piece of silicon that started in the ground as a lump of rock is now the most perfect thing that humankind has ever mass-produced but the deeper you look in that along that supply chain as economists call it the more amazing things you encounter you know we're all touching these devices every day you're watching this thanks to that process of creating a little bit of perfection in all of our pockets and i'm surprised that we don't talk about this more but yes career is is in some ways kind of the ultimate silicon society because it is it is benefiting from this Thank you.",
      "summary": "Ed Conway explains the complex process of turning quartzite into highly pure silicon wafers for chips, noting that even industry workers often don't know the origin of the material."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 266.0,
      "end_time": 304.0,
      "transcript": "So you contrast sort of two conceptual worlds that people live in and most urbanized population you say live in ethereal world. And that's an interesting choice of word because if my knowledge of Western philosophy is correct and you'll correct me if I'm wrong, ether was a concept that evolved because there was no concept for nothingness or emptiness in ancient Greece, right? It's an ancient grace, right? Yeah. In Korea, we are very, very, in East Asia, we are very comfortable with the idea of nothing. I mean, if you look at Taoist text, the entire text is like the word is actually nothing, right? That's ridiculous. Right. That's really interesting. But in Korea, because we didn't have this concept, I think they just translated it to non-material world. or nothing material world. Okay, but that's probably better to be honest with you. But I think ethereal, I think that's a very interesting choice of word because people who are not living in material world, people who are living in the idea of trends and designs and consumer products and branding, they do live in a world composed of some things that's not a thing. So ether, I think, is a perfectly good word.",
      "summary": "The host and Ed Conway discuss the concept of the 'Ethereal World' versus the 'Material World,' touching on philosophical translations and the nature of modern consumer culture."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 304.0,
      "end_time": 342.0,
      "transcript": "Although actually most, a lot of people, I think they don't really think about the internet as a physical set of infrastructure. They think that, you know, you get on your smartphone and you just kind of communicate and then suddenly it's just there somewhere on the web. But the reality is the internet, it's a network of fiber optics. It's physical. The vast majority of the distance that, you know, that this, for instance, will travel is on physical fiber optics. It's on server centers. And all of that is physical. My day job is as an economics journalist, and we spend so much time fixating on gross domestic products, GDP. But I had this nagging suspicion that basically everything we do, even if it's intangible, relies one way or another on the physical infrastructure around us. And so surely that was just worthy of more attention. And economists don't pay much attention to this stuff because it is quite a small fraction of GDP. but I just think there's something wrong with that because basically 99% of GDP still depends on this small part of the economy. We all depend on fertilizers otherwise half of the world's population is not here. We all depend on concrete otherwise we don't have the ability to urbanize. We all depend on copper because without copper you don't have anything electronic working. Like you've got a kind of like a pyramid but it's an upside down pyramid and it's balanced on this tiny little bit point and that tiny little point is the material world and everything else, if that's not there, the whole thing collapses and so we still need it.",
      "summary": "Ed Conway argues that the internet and economy rely on physical infrastructure like fiber optics and raw materials, using an upside-down pyramid analogy to show the material world's foundational role."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 342.0,
      "end_time": 380.0,
      "transcript": "And I think in your book, you say that the most miraculous thing we've done in the 21st century is make material world such a small part of our GDP. Yeah. That we've gotten so good at mining stuff and refining stuff that I guess in the 19th century, all people in the government or corporations thought about is how do we get copper or how do we get iron or how do we get glass? Yeah, or food, for instance. Right, or food. They're food. Yeah, so it's a success story. It's a success story that we don't have to think about this stuff anymore because for a long time, this was the stuff that allowed us to survive.",
      "summary": "The host and Ed Conway agree that making the material world a small part of GDP is a 21st-century miracle, reflecting a success story where survival no longer depends on constant resource extraction."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 380.0,
      "end_time": 418.0,
      "transcript": "so these days when people talk about national security level technology people usually talk about ai code or gpus you know but you talk about how uh when the war between russia and ukraine started there was like a specific type of steel that could only be made in this one steel plant in Ukraine. There's lots of different grades of steel. You know, you've got kind of like construction steels. You've got kind of steels that you use in rebar. You've got electrical steels, really important for transformers. Actually, Ukraine is really important for the production of electrical steel. So it was quite hard for anyone wanting to build transformers, which is pretty important right now. I kind of think actually one of the most important and exciting innovations in the world is transformers because that enables us to send power over long distances and then transform it down into a kind that we can actually use. And we need loads more of these things. And basically, a transformer is just an iron block with lots of copper around it. That's what a transformer is. Just the way the copper is wound is the clever thing. And for a period, actually, when this steel plant in Mariupol went down, it's the famous one where when the Russians invaded, a lot of the ukrainian fighters went into the steel mill and they defended themselves there and they turned it into a fortress but this place was really responsible for a lot of the world's electrical steel it was also responsible for not just the steel but the byproduct of that process of making the steel was also various types of inert gases like neon neon is something that people don't think about much but you need it to make semiconductors and suddenly a plant kind of shutting down in Ukraine was responsible for a big shortage of the stuff that semiconductor plants needed and suddenly computer chip manufacturers being threatened. So it just goes to show the interconnectedness of the world and why one plant making steel might actually be responsible for something else.",
      "summary": "Ed Conway discusses the impact of the Ukraine war on the supply of electrical steel and neon gas, highlighting the interconnectedness of global industries like steel and semiconductors."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 418.0,
      "end_time": 456.0,
      "transcript": "We had another example in the UK recently where there was a plant making fertilizers. One of the byproducts of that fertilizer was carbon dioxide and we use carbon dioxide it's not a very nice story but we use carbon dioxide to slaughter pigs this place this fertilizer plant was responsible for all of the country's carbon dioxide suddenly that plant was shut down because the gas was too expensive because remember fertilizer is is a fossil fuel product that plant shut down we didn't have carbon dioxide we didn't have any pork and no one expected that and people within governments they didn't understand the interconnectedness of the economy and of the world around us but it's so interconnected and there are these unexpected linkages that suddenly they only surface when you start to run out of something",
      "summary": "Ed Conway shares an example of a UK fertilizer plant shutdown causing a pork shortage due to a lack of CO2 for slaughter, illustrating unexpected economic linkages."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 456.0,
      "end_time": 494.0,
      "transcript": "South Korea has two very important economic sectors. We basically make our living by exporting semiconductors and now exporting what they call second-generation batteries, the kind of batteries that are infinitely rechargeable, not infinitely, but rechargeable over several years that form the backbone of either electrical storage systems or electric cars. And you included lithium among six materials that make up human civilization. Does it merit its place within the six? lithium is all is today really really important because that's you know that's the missing link in how we decarbonize transport essentially how we decarbonize storage at least short-term storage maybe long-term storage in future and Korea you know is a big part of that story because this is where a lot of the batteries are being made you know LG Chem uh Samsung you know these are these are big parts of the the story and if we don't make enough batteries to to have all of those electric cars then we're not going to be able to do this it's just not going to happen and what's fascinating about this moment in time is you know we're living through an industrial revolution at the moment",
      "summary": "The host asks about lithium's importance, and Ed Conway confirms its critical role in decarbonizing transport and storage, highlighting South Korea's battery industry."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 494.0,
      "end_time": 532.0,
      "transcript": "that's kind of a big thing we these things don't come around that often this is we you know you had the the famous industrial revolution kind of two three hundred years ago that started in england really you had the various revolutions the electronic revolution that came after that you had different all these different fossil fuels the motor car revolution and oil and gas that came along since then well now we're kind of living through this energy transition which is another form of revolution we need to rethink the way that we are delivering our power we need to rethink the way that we're making pretty much everything so it's lower carbon and a massive part of that is being able to to have transport that doesn't involve burning fossil fuels and batteries obviously are a massive part of that many of us now already own electric cars but that is going to get bigger and bigger but in order to provide enough of those batteries you need a lot of lithium we don't really have like you say that much experience of mining lithium we've got thousands of years of experience of mining copper and slightly less of iron we know how to do that we know how to get salt out of the ground and turn it into various different things the romans were doing that we don't really have that much experience of working with lithium and over the next 20 30 years the amount by the kind of rate at which we have to ratchet up our lithium mining is faster than any other metal we have ever done in our history of humanity so So that's a big challenge.",
      "summary": "Ed Conway describes the current energy transition as a new industrial revolution, noting the unprecedented challenge of scaling lithium mining to meet future demand."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 532.0,
      "end_time": 570.0,
      "transcript": "I see this argument a lot on car forms when, you know, somebody says, I just bought a Tesla and it's much cleaner than a petroleum car. You know, there are obviously people who are very attached to their petroleum cars. And they say, hey, the process that made my car has been in existence for the last hundred years. But in order to build your car, they had to dig a new hole in the ground, like you said, somewhere in Chile. And people had to go down into the pit, mine that in atrocious conditions. You know, lithium's leak, pollute the rivers. And then, petroleum car, if you are willing to do a little work, we can basically keep it running, you know, 30, 40 years, but your battery is going to go bad in about six to seven years, and then you have to, you know, change the entire underside of your car. How is that more environmentally friendly? I'm sure you've heard this a lot, right? A lot, yeah. And you are the only person I know who has visited an actual lithium mine.",
      "summary": "The host raises arguments against electric cars regarding mining conditions and battery lifespan compared to gas cars, noting Ed Conway's unique experience visiting a lithium mine."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 570.0,
      "end_time": 608.0,
      "transcript": "has gone through the entire process of seeing how the batteries made and you even went to the in the book one of the most dramatic sort of visual scene in your book is when you go to the recycling factory for these batteries where you know they take this uh very tightly wound uh battery cells and you take them apart and take them really It's really dangerous, it's really dangerous to take apart a battery as well, because they are, these little things, and we have them inside our pockets, these little things are combustible, they're almost like little weapons. So when you compare the two, like on the ground, Are you convinced now that lithium is the future? I'm convinced that lithium and batteries are a big part of the answer. But I agree with you. It is much more complex than a lot of people often make out. And I think part of the problem with the way that the whole debate, the political conversation has been had, is that I suppose politicians have been reluctant to tell people that some of this stuff might be difficult. Some of this stuff might involve compromises. Some of this stuff might be expensive as well. And also that getting to net zero and achieving all of these goals can sometimes be quite dirty. And it does involve digging new holes in the ground. And it does involve compromises. And getting hold of cobalt is really difficult. You know, the vast majority of the world's supply of cobalt comes from the Democratic Republic of Congo. The conditions in the mines there are terrible. These places are not clean places. But we live in a world that is, this is not a world of black and white. You know, all of these decisions involve trade-offs, as economists would call them.",
      "summary": "Ed Conway discusses the dangers of battery recycling and agrees that the transition to lithium is complex, involving difficult trade-offs and compromises regarding mining conditions and environmental impact."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 608.0,
      "end_time": 646.0,
      "transcript": "And I just think the trade-offs are greater for fossil fuels than they are for the alternative. But I also think by the same token, there's no way we can't just cut ourselves off from oil. I do think electric cars are better than petrol cars. So with oil, a lot of people think, oh, we can just end our reliance on fossil fuels and then everything is fine. We are nowhere near that. There are still so many areas where we still don't know how to make the fossil fuel product as well as we can make the sustainable products. I mean, an example I like to give is Lego. They're made out of something called ABS, its type of plastic, acrylonitrile butadine styrene. It's made from petrochemicals, basically from oil and from gas. And you go through lots of different processes and you come out with this really hard type of plastic called ABS. Lego have spent a long time experimenting with different plastics to get to ABS. and it's the perfect thing. It doesn't lose its colour. It doesn't lose its shape. It can be kind of moulded into really precise forms. They've been working for the last five, six years or so to try to come up with a plastic that is sustainable and it's as good as ABS and they haven't been able to come up with anything. And that's just, obviously, that's just a toy. But there's certain things that fossil fuels do really well and we are still unable to replicate them. The other thing we could talk about is fertilisers. A lot of people think, you know, we have protests a lot of the time in the UK about fossil fuels. And I saw one person wearing a t-shirt one time, because they're trying to campaign to stop oil production in the UK. And I think that's a noble thing to be aiming to do. But I saw one person wearing a t-shirt saying, you can't eat oil. But the reality is, we all eat oil on a daily basis.",
      "summary": "Ed Conway argues that fossil fuels are still essential for products like Lego and fertilizers, noting that sustainable alternatives are not yet viable and that we essentially 'eat oil' through our food."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 646.0,
      "end_time": 684.0,
      "transcript": "Because another shocking visual from your book is when you say most of the tomatoes that are grown today are not planted the way they were like 100 years ago. But if you go to these high-tech farms, right, the tomato is basically sitting on some kind of waterbed with fossil fuel-based fertilizers running through them. So tomato is actually eating oil. Yep. And we are... Natural gas. Natural gas. That's your guess, okay. Is that better? I'm not sure. And when you're eating tomato, you're actually eating fossil fuel. Yeah. We're not just putting oil in the car, we're actually putting oil in our bodies, right? Yes, we are. Exactly that. And that's where we get our energy from. And that's where the fertiliser that feeds us comes from. And it still begins with fossil fuels. And we are still nowhere near coming up with a better way of getting fertilisers.",
      "summary": "The host and Ed Conway discuss how modern farming relies on fossil fuel-based fertilizers, meaning that eating vegetables like tomatoes is effectively consuming fossil fuels."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 684.0,
      "end_time": 722.0,
      "transcript": "And I'm somewhat of a history nerd, so one of the more interesting parts of your book is where you talk about the World War I and World War II. Because when you think about World War I, you usually think about the Eastern Front and the Western Front and big population centers in Europe. But you said some very important battles were being fought in the Pacific over Bad Dung. So essentially, before we worked out how to make fertilizers out of fossil fuels, we used to have to mine the stuff out of the ground, nitrogen. Essentially, there's three types of things you really need to grow crops. It's nitrogen, phosphorus and potassium, NPK as they call them. And nitrogen is the most important because that promotes the growth of the plants. And back at kind of like 150 years ago, the best form of nitrogen that we had discovered was bird droppings and bat droppings guano as it's sometimes called and the the places where we found the most of this were on these old deserted pacific islands i think because of just the climatic conditions meant that places in peru and in chile just islands off the coast they had these thick crusts of bird droppings that had just had just accreted over hundreds if not thousands of years and it just dried there and people discovered that this stuff if you put it onto the ground if you crumbled it up and put it on the ground it promoted growth and it meant that you had this amazing amazing fertilizer and so when this stuff was discovered there was a massive race for it and countries around the world were competing to try and get a hold of this stuff and the early and eventually they actually ran out of the bird droppings and then they found a mineral form of it in in uh in chile and this stuff was so important it was it was sought after all around the world because your ability to to grow crops and feed your population depended on getting hold of this nitrogen and so when the first world war started one of the first big battles that happened was over the the sea light lanes which would control the supply of this stuff from chile all the way through to to europe and so germany wanted it and also the uk and and the other allies wanted it as well and so actually that was one of the first big battles was was there but even before that there'd been a war between Chile and Bolivia over the control of the these territories where they got hold of this stuff called caliche and this is a mineral that we don't even think about today and the reason we don't think about it today is because because the Germans were so desperate for it back in World War One and because they couldn't get hold of it because we blocked the shipping lanes they then encouraged their scientists to try and come up with a kind of an artificial alternative and that is where this revolution in turning fossil fuels it started off as coal and then it was oil and then now it's natural gas turning that into nitrogen came from the harbour bosch process a guy called fritz harbour came up with this process of turning fossil fuels and hydrogen that we get from them into fertilizer and part of the reason actually that we have not run out of fertilizer and we haven't run out of food you know we still that we are able to feed the global population of 8 billion people is because of that innovation. And that innovation happened because of those battles at the start of World War I. And they're battles that no one remembers now for the control of a substance that no one remembers now. But they're part of the reason why we're all alive now.",
      "summary": "Ed Conway explains the historical importance of guano and caliche as nitrogen sources, leading to wars and the eventual development of the Haber-Bosch process for artificial fertilizer, which sustains the global population today."
    },
    {
      "start_time": 722.0,
      "end_time": 760.0,
      "transcript": "When you look at the six substances, you have to wonder what would happen to human life if one of them would eventually run out. So when I was in primary school, on the news, it was very big news when we were going to run out of oil. I don't know why we don't talk about that anymore. Now we, because of the electrical revolution. revolution because we well no it's partly because we didn't run out of oil and because you know america the shale revolution they discovered more oil that we just we just got really good at finding new ways of getting stuff out of the ground and and so fracking basically solved that And, you know, back then, people were saying that we might run out of oil if we keep at current rates. So current rate back in the 1990s was much slower than current rate now. They said, oh, we'll run out of oil in 50 years or 60 years. I remember this very clearly. One news story said that if you drove by the Sofitel Hotel in Seoul, you might have seen a big sports complex. And before we held our Olympics in 1988, that was one of the biggest buildings in Korea, Jang Chung Chewokwan. and the news would say today koreans burned six jangchung chihokan worth of oil and that would be in the news and we need to like turn down our thermostats and try to save oil because we don't produce any and the world is eventually going to run out but you said there was a panic around running out of copper about 100 years ago too and we never think about running out of copper either so what was the whole deal with people thinking we're running out of copper it.",
      "summary": "The host recalls past panics about running out of oil and copper, asking Ed Conway about the historical context of these resource fears."
    },
    {
